=3D"620"><span class=3D"caption">Shasta Lake, California=E2=80=99s largest =
reservoir, has a storage capacity of 4.55 million acre-feet. Source: U.S. B=
ureau of Reclamation</span></a></span></div>
          <div class=3D"node-content content node-item">
            <p>
  An acre-foot is a common way in the U.S. to measure water volume
  and use. It is the amount of water it takes to cover an acre of
  land one foot deep. An acre is about the size of a football
  field.
</p>
<p>
  An acre-foot of water equals 325,851 gallons, and historically
  that was enough to serve the needs of&nbsp;two families for a
  year in California.
</p>
<p>
  In 2018, with many people using less water,&nbsp;Metropolitan
  Water District of Southern California=E2=80=99s service area <a href=3D"h=
ttps://www.watereducation.org/western-water/water-stressed-california-and-s=
outhwest-acre-foot-water-goes-lot-further-it-used">
  reported an acre-foot&nbsp;was enough to supply about three homes
  a year</a>.
</p>
<p>
  An acre-foot of water continues to go considerably further than
  it used to in meeting California=E2=80=99s urban water needs, depending
  on the region,&nbsp;because <a href=3D"https://www.ppic.org/publication/w=
ater-use-in-california/" class=3D"ext" target=3D"_blank">per-capita
  water use has been steadily falling.</a><span class=3D"ext"></span>
</p>
<p>
  Other common acre-foot measurements:
</p>
<ul>
  <li>The federal&nbsp;<a href=3D"https://www.watereducation.org/aquapedia/=
central-valley-project">Central Valley
  Project</a>&nbsp;delivers about 7 million acre-feet of water
  annually for agricultural, urban and wildlife uses in years of
  normal precipitation.
  </li>
  <li>The&nbsp;<a href=3D"https://www.watereducation.org/aquapedia/state-wa=
ter-project">State Water
  Project</a>&nbsp;delivered an average of <a href=3D"https://data.cnra.ca.=
gov/dataset/state-water-project-delivery-capability-report-dcr-2021/resourc=
e/5721288c-9553-477e-8738-774ea2ff537e" class=3D"ext" target=3D"_blank">
    1.8 million acre-feet annually</a><span class=3D"ext"></span> to munici=
pal, industrial and
    agricultural users between 2011 and 2020.
  </li>
  <li>Shasta Lake, California=E2=80=99s largest reservoir, has a storage
  capacity of 4.55 million acre-feet. This amount&nbsp;would cover
  the entire state in about a half inch of water.
  </li>
</ul>
<p>
  <span class=3D"field-image field-not-video field-image-preset-medium crop=
